Sgt Jason Thomas enlisted in the Marine Corps in 1996 and closed out his active-duty service in the Spring of 2001. While attending law school in NYC, he was dropping off his two-year-old daughter at his mother’s house when he first heard the news of the attacks on the World Trade Center. He immediately put on the camouflage utilities still in the trunk of his car and began driving toward Manhattan. 
 
As he exited his parked vehicle and turned to walk toward the epicenter of the chaos, the first tower’s collapse engulfed him in a storm of asphyxiating heat and debris. Listen here to this exemplary Marine’s experience at Ground Zero. Once a Marine, always a Marine. Semper Fidelis. #MarinesRemember911 #WeRemember911

On 9/11, LCpl Sarah Rudder (ret.) was among those Marines from a detachment near the Pentagon who ran to scene in the moments after the plane hit. 

Despite sustaining significant injuries while aiding in search, rescue, and recovery efforts, she and her fellow Marines continue for 24 hours until more help could arrive. 

Follow this video series via #MarinesRemember911. Semper Fidelis. #WeRemember911

node.text:
Col. David Ashe was visiting his parents in Virginia Beach, VA during his final days of active-duty service as a Marine when the 9/11 attacks occurred. Without hesitation, then-Capt Ashe donned his camouflage utility uniform, drove to Ground Zero, and began to render aid as part of the Bucket Brigades. 

Upon returning home, he would decide to continue serving in the Marine Corps. His courageous charge toward the sounds of chaos reflects the very essence of the phrase: Semper Fidelis. Always faithful. 

#MarinesRemember911 #WeRemember911

Born in Las Vegas, NV in July 2000 to first generation Cuban immigrants, Lance Cpl. Valdes shares how his parents and teachers conveyed their experience of 9/11 to him from a young age, and how the event, along with his deep desire to serve his country, shaped his decision to join the United States Marine Corps. Follow this video series via #MarinesRemember911. Semper Fidelis. #WeRemember911 

Interview Date: August 3, 2021

Over the next three days, we will share stories of how Marines, from those still on active duty to those who have returned to civilian life, have been impacted by the events that occurred on that fateful day in September 20 years ago. 

In the first video of our #MarinesRemember911 series, Col. Lance Lewis, the commanding officer of Marine Corps Air Station Iwakuni, speaks about his memories of 9/11 and his experience as one of the first Marines engaged in combat in Afghanistan supporting Operation Enduring Freedom. Follow this video series via #MarinesRemember911. Semper Fidelis. #WeRemember911

Interview Date: August 27, 2021

Based on a threat-informed, ten-year time horizon, the Marine Corps is designing a force for naval expeditionary warfare in actively contested spaces. Throughout this ten-year initiative, the Marine Corps will make investments in capabilities to include long range precision fires, advanced reconnaissance capabilities, unmanned systems, and resilient networks. (U.S. Marine Corps video by Cpl. Nicholas Filca)

For more information, view the link in the bio.

node.text:
Sgt Jason Thomas enlisted in the Marine Corps in 1996 and closed out his active-duty service in the Spring of 2001. While attending law school in NYC, he was dropping off his two-year-old daughter at his mother’s house when he first heard the news of the attacks on the World Trade Center. He immediately put on the camouflage utilities still in the trunk of his car and began driving toward Manhattan. 
 
As he exited his parked vehicle and turned to walk toward the epicenter of the chaos, the first tower’s collapse engulfed him in a storm of asphyxiating heat and debris. Listen here to this exemplary Marine’s experience at Ground Zero. Once a Marine, always a Marine. Semper Fidelis. #MarinesRemember911 #WeRemember911

Col. David Ashe was visiting his parents in Virginia Beach, VA during his final days of active-duty service as a Marine when the 9/11 attacks occurred. Without hesitation, then-Capt Ashe donned his camouflage utility uniform, drove to Ground Zero, and began to render aid as part of the Bucket Brigades. 

Upon returning home, he would decide to continue serving in the Marine Corps. His courageous charge toward the sounds of chaos reflects the very essence of the phrase: Semper Fidelis. Always faithful. 

#MarinesRemember911 #WeRemember911

Helping Hand

#Marines interact with Afghan children at @mcbquantico, September 1, 2021, during Operation Allies Welcome.

The @deptofdefense through U.S. Northern Command, and in support of the @dhsgov, is providing transportation, temporary housing, medical screening, and general support for up to 50,000 Afghan evacuees at suitable facilities, in permanent or temporary structures, as quickly as possible. 

This initiative provides Afghan personnel essential support at secure locations outside Afghanistan. 

#USMC #Military 

(U.S. Marine Corps photo by Sergeant Kaitlynn M. Hendricks)

node.text:
Night's Watch

U.S. Marine Corps Sgt. Aaron Palomino, the chief scout sniper with Weapons Company, Battalion Landing Team 1/1, 11th Marine Expeditionary Unit, sets security with an M110 Semi-Automatic Sniper System aboard amphibious assault ship USS Essex (LHD 2), Sept. 2, 2021. 

Essex, flagship of the Essex Amphibious Ready Group, along with the 11th MEU, is operating in the U.S. 7th Fleet area of responsibility to enhance interoperability with allies and partners and serve as a ready response force to defend peace and stability in the Indo-Pacific region. (U.S. Marine Corps photo by Cpl. Israel Chincio)

Up and Away

A CH-53E Super Stallion helicopter assigned to Marine Heavy Helicopter Squadron (HMH) 463 hoists a Joint Light Tactical Vehicle during hoist operations training on Marine Corps Base Hawaii, September 2, 2021.
